About
Beautiful Victorian cemetery near to Hampstead Heath. Highgate Cemetery has some of the finest funerary architecture in the country. It is a place of peaceful contemplation where trees, memorials and wildlife flourish.
Duration: 2-3 hours

A self-guided walk around the more manicured East-side (which is included in the ticket price) is also interesting with a variety of famous people buried there from Karl Marx to Malcom McLaren. Evangelina27
London, UK147 contributions
A Victorian Haven of Peace and Tranquillity
Oct 2024 Family
I live in North London and I hadn't been to visit the cemetery for a while but thought it might be an interesting half-term visit for my 11 year-old and her father, neither of whom had previously visited. Both are interested in history and I thought learning some local history would make the trip even more engaging, being that we live in the area. As an amateur photographer, I was also really excited about taking some autumnal snaps as well as revelling in the peaceful nature of the cemetery. Unfortunately my daughter had a fainting spell right at the beginning of the tour. Our wonderful tour guide couldn't have been more helpful. He immediately contacted his manager who was prepared to arrange for an ambulance although we said this wouldn't be necessary. He arrived on a vehicle ready to take her to have something to eat which was just what she needed. My partner insisted I continue on the tour on my own as he knew how much I'd been looking forward to it. I'd been on 2 previous tours, a long time ago, and although covering highlights at the cemetery, each guide brought their own insights to the tour which made for a slightly different experience each time. Terry was no exception. As a North Londoner, he clearly had a passion for the cemetery and its history and he enlightened us with many amusing and informative anecdotes along the way. He very kindly checked in on my daughter's condition while I was messaging my partner to see how she was doing - she was having a lovely time being given Custard Cream biscuits by the manager which she was delighting in sharing with Amber the resident fox!
As a nature enthusiast it was wonderful to witness the diversity of the birdlife, the cute squirrels who were busily gathering food for the winter, and the foxes who periodically popped up in flashes of orange amidst the greys of the gravestones, and the greens and browns of autumnal foliage. After the tour had ended, I went back into the cemetery to wander beyond the areas we'd covered on the tour and I was struck by the peace and tranquillity of the place. Had my family not been waiting for me, I'd have certainly spent a lot longer in the cemetery, reflecting and wandering around the gothic majesty of the Victorian architecture. All in all, it was a wonderful experience for me and I hope to share it again with my daughter soon. Furthermore, I was very impressed by the staff who rallied around to support her when she was feeling unwell, and I was very touched by the manager who kindly refunded both my partner and daughter's tickets completely unprompted. A big thank you to all of the staff at Highgate Cemetery.
Written November 5, 2024

How long do you reckon you need comfortably to look around Highgate cemetery?
Written June 4, 2019
B G
Canada
28 contributions
The tour of the west side itself (which you shouldnt miss) will take about 1.5 hours. Then your own viewing of the east side, which is just as big, is of course up to you. Id say at least hour, depending on how you usually contemplate yourself through cemeteries. And if you are tubing it, youll need to walk up a fairly hefty hill. It isnt super far, but will take you 15-20 minutes to walk. And then a lovely 10 minute stroll through a park at the top just to get to the cemetery gates. Driving of course will be different. But in foot, if you through in a coffee or a beer into your post-itinerary itll take you even longer. First tour on Sat was 10 am if I remember correctly and I wasnt back at the tube station till 1:30. All being said, if you have the time, absolutely do it. It is a fascinating look at Victorian stones, and our tour guide was SUPER informative. Hope that is helpful. Cheers.

452 contributions
The cemetery is divided into East and West sections. The East section is open to the public, but also offers occasional guided tours. The West section is ONLY open via a guided tour conducted by an official Highgate volunteer. You can book these tours via the website or at the onsite ticket office. We took the West section guided tour and it's definitely worth the time and cost.
